#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:4
msgid "Marking test functions with attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:6
msgid ""
"By using the ``pytest.mark`` helper you can easily set metadata on your test "
"functions. There are some builtin markers, for example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:10
msgid ":ref:`skip <skip>` - always skip a test function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:11
msgid ""
":ref:`skipif <skipif>` - skip a test function if a certain condition is met"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:12
msgid ""
":ref:`xfail <xfail>` - produce an \"expected failure\" outcome if a certain "
"condition is met"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:14
msgid ""
":ref:`parametrize <parametrizemark>` to perform multiple calls to the same "
"test function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:17
msgid ""
"It's easy to create custom markers or to apply markers to whole test classes "
"or modules. Those markers can be used by plugins, and also are commonly used "
"to :ref:`select tests <mark run>` on the command-line with the ``-m`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:21
msgid ""
"See :ref:`mark examples` for examples which also serve as documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:25
msgid ""
"Marks can only be applied to tests, having no effect on :ref:`fixtures "
"<fixtures>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:30
msgid "Registering marks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:32
msgid "You can register custom marks in your ``pytest.ini`` file like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:34
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"markers =\n"
"    slow: marks tests as slow (deselect with '-m \"not slow\"')\n"
"    serial"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:41
msgid "Note that everything after the ``:`` is an optional description."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:43
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can register new markers programatically in a :ref:"
"`pytest_configure <initialization-hooks>` hook:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:46
msgid ""
"def pytest_configure(config):\n"
"    config.addinivalue_line(\n"
"        \"markers\", \"env(name): mark test to run only on named "
"environment\"\n"
"    )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:54
msgid ""
"Registered marks appear in pytest's help text and do not emit warnings (see "
"the next section). It is recommended that third-party plugins always :ref:"
"`register their markers <registering-markers>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:60
msgid "Raising errors on unknown marks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:62
msgid ""
"Unregistered marks applied with the ``@pytest.mark.name_of_the_mark`` "
"decorator will always emit a warning in order to avoid silently doing "
"something surprising due to mis-typed names. As described in the previous "
"section, you can disable the warning for custom marks by registering them in "
"your ``pytest.ini`` file or using a custom ``pytest_configure`` hook."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:68
msgid ""
"When the ``--strict-markers`` command-line flag is passed, any unknown marks "
"applied with the ``@pytest.mark.name_of_the_mark`` decorator will trigger an "
"error. You can enforce this validation in your project by adding ``--strict-"
"markers`` to ``addopts``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/mark.rst:72
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = --strict-markers\n"
"markers =\n"
"    slow: marks tests as slow (deselect with '-m \"not slow\"')\n"
"    serial"
msgstr ""
